3-Axis MEMS Method — X/Y/Z Configuration

This experimental version of the project uses three independent MEMS MPU6050 gyroscopes oriented along the X, Y, and Z axes.

The goal of this configuration is not only to measure rotation about a single axis, but primarily to:

- analyze correlations between axes
- separate mechanical artifacts
- identify system drift
- compare long-term stability of individual sensors
- enable advanced statistical filtering
- detect common and differential signals between axes

System configuration:

Gyro X → measures rotation around the X axis
Gyro Y → measures rotation around the Y axis
Gyro Z → measures rotation around the Z axis

Each sensor will be:

- mechanically rigidly mounted
- thermally stabilized
- placed on a shared anti-vibration platform
- synchronously sampled

The main idea of the project is to compare the behavior of individual axes in long-term measurements.

A single MEMS gyro:

- suffers from drift
- reacts to vibrations
- is sensitive to temperature
- generates random noise

Using three mutually orthogonal sensors enables:

- comparison of behavior across axes
- detection of correlated changes
- identification of mechanical disturbances
- separation of random drift from common effects

If a change appears:

only in one axis → likely a local artifact
simultaneously in multiple axes → potentially a system-wide phenomenon

Mechanical vibrations often produce characteristic signatures in specific axes. A 3-axis configuration enables their identification, filtering, and subsequent FFT analysis.

Each MEMS sensor drifts differently. Comparing the X, Y, and Z axes allows estimation of system stability, long-term statistical evaluation, and monitoring of temperature effects.

The project uses a multi-layer anti-vibration structure:

motor base
↓
main rotating bearing
↓
heavy rotating platform
↓
vibration isolation
↓
gyro platform

Main goals of the mechanical design:

- minimization of vibrations
- elimination of cable drag effects
- high mass symmetry
- thermal stability
- autonomous operation

The control unit of the project is a Raspberry Pi Pico 2 WH.

Implemented functions:

- synchronous IMU reading
- local data logging
- Wi-Fi data transmission
- time synchronization

The used MPU6050 / GY-521 sensors include:

3-axis gyroscope
3-axis accelerometer
internal temperature sensor

The system also includes a separate DHT11 temperature and humidity sensor.

The system is designed as:

- fully autonomous
- battery powered
- without moving data or power cables

The goals are:

- elimination of mechanical interference
- reduction of EMI
- long-term stable measurements

Planned future extensions:

- multiple synchronized IMUs
- more precise mechanical platform
- active thermal stabilization
- FFT spectral analysis
- automatic drift compensation
- long-term statistical measurements
- comparison of different MEMS technologies

